{"type":"message","id":"2b046b61","parentId":"2535fd75","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:48:26.022Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The entitlements log shows that `com.unity.editor.headless` was granted as `True` at 10:46:18.867. But the error in the log shows `License is not active (com.unity.editor.headless). HasEntitlements will fail.`\n\nThis suggests that the entitlements were successfully granted at some point (when running from Unity Hub), but when running in batchmode directly from cmd, it fails.\n\nWait - the log from the successful entitlement check was from 10:46 (today's date), which was when I started Unity Hub earlier. So Unity Hub DOES have a valid license and can grant entitlements.\n\nThe issue is that when running Unity.exe directly from command line (without Hub supervising it), it can't validate the license file. The error `Cannot load ULF license: The digital signature is invalid.` is the core issue.\n\nActually, looking more carefully - the entitlement was granted to the license group `F4-H1R5-BQNV-8DQZ-Q4V2-XXXX`, which is a valid personal license. But the ULF file has an invalid signature.\n\nLet me try a different approach: since Unity Hub was able to grant entitlements earlier (it's still running), maybe I should:\n1. Kill all Unity processes\n2. Start Unity Hub\n3. Run through Unity Hub with -projectPath to open the project\n4. But I need batchmode...\n\nActually, what if I use the Unity Hub's own method of launching? Unity Hub has a command line interface.\n\nActually, let me take a step back. This seems like a license issue that needs human intervention. The user needs to re-activate their Unity license. This could be done through Unity Hub by clicking \"Manage License\" and re-activating.\n\nHowever, the user's note says \"首次使用需在 Unity Editor 中打开 BuildPipeline 窗口配置好\" which implies they expect to run this manually the first time.\n\nI think the best approach now is to:\n1. Report back that the Unity license is invalid/corrupted \n2. The user needs to open Unity Hub, sign in, and re-activate the license\n3. Or run the bat file from an admin PowerShell/CMD prompt\n\nLet me try one more thing - maybe I can use the Unity Hub's built-in CLI to launch the editor with proper license context.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_p3Ukxte0odXJSSIuKfjM7467","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Kill all Unity processes, then try running via Unity Hub's command\nGet-Process \"Unity Hub\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Stop-Process -Force\nGet-Process \"Unity\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Stop-Process -Force\nGet-Process \"Unity.Licensing.Client\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Stop-Process -Force\nStart-Sleep -Seconds 3\n\n# Check if Unity Hub has CLI options\n& \"C:\\Program Files\\Unity Hub\\Unity Hub.exe\" --help 2>&1 | Select -First 20","timeout":15}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":3388,"output":671,"cacheRead":33536,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":37595,"cost":{"input":0.00047432,"output":0.00018788000000000002,"cacheRead":0.000939008,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.001601208}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778755699615,"responseId":"5e8d81af-aa8b-4678-a143-274cc4dabbb9"}}
